explanation:
OS_console_internal_record_t - needed to see the types of its fields (BufBase, ReadPos, WritePos, BufSize). In particular BufBase element/type (e.g. char * vs const char *) determines whether the buffer pointer could/should be const and whether the function modifies the pointed-to data. Also ReadPos is written at the end, which affects whether the console pointer itself could be const.

OS_console_table - the global table object (type/constness) used with OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET; its declaration can show whether table elements are stored as mutable or const records and how the lookup is expected to be used.

OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET - macro/function that performs the lookup; its prototype/definition determines the exact return type (pointer to mutable or const OS_console_internal_record_t) and whether the dereference of *token is used in a way that would require token mutability.

OS_BSP_ConsoleOutput_Impl - prototype is required to know the parameter types (does it accept const void*/const char* or non-const?). This determines whether passing &console->BufBase[StartPos] should use a const-qualified pointer or not (and whether the call would discard const qualification).

OS_object_token_t - the typedef/underlying type of the token to confirm whether the function parameter const OS_object_token_t *token is appropriately const-qualified and whether any use of *token (passed into OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET) would require token mutability.
